22 ELPENORA who, when Ulixes left the palace of Circe, hearing the bustle, rose hastily to join his mates. and falling backward broke his neck (Od. X 552—560); Ulixes saw his shade in Hades (XI 51—83). Homer does not mention by name the twenty-one of the crew who were transformed by Circe's wand, and consequently does not expressly include Elpenor among them (X 135—46S): but he represents him as breaking his neck by a fall in drunken sleep, and therefore a very fit inmate of Circe's Sty.
